AB  - The Sierra de Atapuerca, Burgos, Spain, contains numerous modern and ancient caves. Cueva Mayor includes a deep shaft, Sima de los Huesos (SH), with abundant human fossils. A railway cut (Trinchera) exposes three major sections: Gran Dolina (GD), Galeria JG), Sima del Elefante (TE), 13-20 in thick, filled with stratified fossiliferous deposits.
   The upper GD layers, late TD8 to TD11 beds, reveal three major climate oscillations and several minor ones; yield mammal remains correlated with Arago, Bilzingsleben, Swanscombe, Malagrotta; are dated 300-400 ka BP; contain lithic assemblages transitional from Mode 2 to Mode 3 and evidence of lasting occupation of a shelter after roof collapse. In the mid TD8 unit there is a gap free of materials coming from outside the cavity. The lower GD units (TD2 to lower TD8) include sediments accumulated when the deep cavity had an early lateral opening up to when the latter was eventually obstructed. Four to five major thermic fluctuations have been detected, together with several minor ones. The lower TD8 is dated c. 600 ka BP, while TD6 is dated c. 800 ka BP. The Matuyama/Brunhes (M/B) reversal occurs in TD7, while the basal TD2 unit is younger than the Jaramillo polarity subzone. A succession of mammal assemblages has been found from TD3 on. These faunas resemble those from Untermassfeld, Vallonnet, Solilhac, Huescar, Nagyharsanyhegy; they are therefore those of the transitional phase that leads to the upper Biharian. Mode 1 lithic artifacts occur from the upper TD4 unit. Evolved Mode 1 lithic artifacts occur throughout the TD6 unit. Evidence of occupation, tool-making, meat consumption and cannibalism has been observed in TD6's upper part, in its so-called "Aurora" Bed. Nearly 100 human fossils have been classified as Homo antecessor.
   The upper and middle units of TG site contain a succession of over ten fossil-bearing horizons. These contain remains of large mammals fallen through a pitfall, which shows evidence of both canid scavenging and human actions, as well as advanced, Mode 2 artifacts. A lower unit, which can be dated over 400 ka BP, yields Mode 2 artifacts as well as evidence of short-lasting occupation and access through a former entrance, now obstructed. Two human fossils were found in the TG middle beds.
   The SH site in Cueva Mayor was full of bones of Ursus deningeri and other carnivores, overlying thousands of human fossils compressed into a narrow clayish mass. The high number of specimens allowed both paleoepidemiological and paleodemographic studies. The evidence indicates a mass annihilation of humans that had sheltered from heavy rain into the cave and that had then been caught up in a landslip. Scavengers may have entered thereafter, and corpses were ultimately dragged into the deep SH shaft by mud. Further collapse moved the mass down into a deeper spot, under a shattered speleothem of more than 350 ka BP. All this caused a stratigraphic inversion: in fact, the human bones are dated c. 320 ka BP. The SH population is assigned to Homo heidelbergensis, which are regarded as the ancestors of the Neanderthals; they most likely originated from the African Bodo deme.
   The Sima del Elefante cut is being excavated and is promising. Its bottom exceeds 1.1 Ma BP on the basis of archaeological evidence, while the top contains fauna, tools and hearths referred to the MIS 5 episode. Portals of two modem caves, which yielded protohistoric Recent remains, are also being excavated, while newly discovered Palaeolithic to Bronce Age sites are being surveyed in different places around the Sierra. Generations to come will still have much to do.
