TI  - TOWARDS GLOBAL RETRIEVAL OF FIELD-SCALE SURFACE SOIL MOISTURE USING L-BAND SAR DATA
T2  - 2022 IEEE INTERNATIONAL GEOSCIENCE AND REMOTE SENSING SYMPOSIUM (IGARSS 2022)
LA  - English
CP  - IEEE International Geoscience and Remote Sensing Symposium (IGARSS)
KW  - soil moisture
KW  - synthetic aperture radar
AB  - We present recent advances in physics-based inversion to retrieve surface soil moisture (of similar to top 5 cm) at field scales. Our goal is to demonstrate the general applicability of the approach with a view to utilizing for the future NASA-ISRO synthetic aperture radar (NISAR) mission, mapping the globe every 6 days with 60-100 m spatial resolution. In the first example, for the agricultural cases in Canada, the soil moisture estimates are accurate to unbiased rmse of 0.041, 0.059 and 0.060 m(3)/m(3) and correlation of 0.71, 0.83, and 0.69 for grass, wheat, and soybean fields, respectively over the soil moisture dynamic range up to 0.5 m(3)/m(3), and soybean's full growth cycle. Second, over Canadian aspen forests, the retrievals over the full dynamic ranges of wetness are accurate to 0.04 m(3)/m(3) unbiased rmse with correlations of 0.71 to 0.84, which is very encouraging for retrieval under the forest canopy. The next two cases present independent validation. Third, in land-slide occurring steep hills (similar to 15 degrees slope) in northern California, 6-m resolution maps of surface soil moisture were generated with unbiased rmse of 0.054 m(3)/m(3), paving ways for understanding and predicting landslide dynamics. Last, when applied to the SMEX02 field campaign datasets, the algorithm provided the unbiased rmse of the retrieved soil moisture at 0.047 m(3)/m(3) and 0.038 m(3)/m(3) for corn and soybean, respectively. In summary, the approach was validated successfully over croplands, steep terrains, and forests.
