TI  - Seismic upgrades techniques of improving post earthquake reliability of pipelines
T2  - OPTIMIZING POST-EARTHQUAKE LIFELINE SYSTEM RELIABILITY
LA  - English
CP  - 5th United States Conference on Lifeline Earthquake Engineering
AB  - East Bay Municipal Utility District's facilities will undergo substantial damage resulting from earthquakes occurring within its service area as well as nearby earthquakes. The District has undertaken a Seismic Improvement Program (SIP) to upgrade its facilities to minimize such damage and to provide speedy recovery of the distribution system. One of the subprograms within the SIP is to provide seismic upgrades for improving post earthquake reliability of pipelines.
   Service level goals of the pipeline upgrades include reducing the risk to the public, water quality issues, and fire and water service. Subject pipelines included for mitigation measures are selected based on fault, liquefaction, and landslide hazards. These hazards have been identified by field investigations and existing geotechnical publications and transposed on to the District's Pipeline Maps.
   Fault crossing zones typically can be identified with a higher certainty than landslide and liquefaction zones; therefore, the District has commenced mitigation of large diameter pipelines at the onset of the SIP. Mitigation upgrades used in past fault crossing projects have been: automatic valves; pipeline re-routes across fault zone; isolation valves with emergency by-passes for the installation of temporary above ground flexible hoses; and the installation of high density polyethylene pipes which provides greater ductility and flexibility than steel pipes.
   On the other hand, backbone piping, the main pipeline that conveys water from a pumping plant to a reservoir, are being mitigated against the less certain landslides and liquefaction hazards; thus, mitigation has commenced several years after the fault crossing upgrades. In certain cases, backbone piping traverses both landslide and fault hazards. Coordination efforts are now being undertaken to merge the landslide, liquefaction, and fault crossing projects. Sequencing planning, design and construction work mitigating these hazards has become one of the most important factors in developing construction bid packages. Construction of these upgrades will continue until the year 2006.
