TI  - NEW AND LITTLE-KNOWN TAXA OF RHYTIDOCHROTINAE (ACRIDIDAE, ORTHOPTERA) FROM COSTA-RICA
T2  - REVUE SUISSE DE ZOOLOGIE
LA  - English
KW  - ORTHOPTERA
KW  - ACRIDIDAE
KW  - RHYTIDOCHROTINAE
KW  - COSTA RICA
KW  - TAXONOMY
AB  - Three new monospecific genera are described from montane areas of Costa Rica. Like the other three known Costa Rican rhytidochrotine genera (Hylopedetes Rehn, 1929, Scirtopaon Descamps & Rowell, 1984 and Micropaon Descamps & Rowell, 1984) they belong to the atympanate and apterous division of the subfamily. All are apparently confined to small geographical areas. Exerythracris is volcanica n.sp. is a fern eater from the light, gaps and edges of montane forest, and resembles in gross morphology the similarly specialised Hylopedetes. It is the most northerly representative of the subfamily so far described, extending almost to the Costa Rican/Nicaraguan border. Brackeracris varablancensis n.sp. is found in successional areas (landslips, anthropogenically altered habitats) in montane forest; its diet is unknown, but does not apparently include ferns; morphologically it is closest to Scirtopaon. Talamancacris palustris n.sp. is confined to a few relict subalpine swamps and appears to eat Asteraceae preferentially; it is not obviously closely allied to the other genera. Additionally, new morphological, ecological and biogeographic data are given for the three previously described genera.
