TI  - Miami International Airport APMs and the airport development
T2  - AUTOMATED PEOPLE MOVERS VI: CREATIVE ACCESS FOR MAJOR ACTIVITY CENTERS
LA  - English
CP  - 6th International Conference on Automated People Movers
AB  - The Dade County Aviation Department (DCAD) has embarked on a redevelopment program for Miami International Airport (MIA), one of the busiest and fastest growing airports in North America. The redevelopment program includes a wide array of projects ranging from existing terminal modifications to new runway construction. These projects are planned to accommodate the airport's forecasted growth through the year 2010. In addition, DCAD is also conducting a strategic terminal planning study to identify terminal development options beyond 2010. As part of the ongoing redevelopment program and long-term strategic plan, Automated People Mover (APM) systems have been planned on the airside and landside to facilitate transportation of airport users.
   The airside and landside APMs will serve both origin/destination and connecting air passengers sir MIA. The two airside APMs will be located in secure areas and transport users traveling between gates and landside facilities and between gates within the same concourse. The landside APM is planned to loop in front of the terminal and transport connecting passengers traveling between concourses. In addition, this system will link the MIA terminal with the planned Miami Intermodal Center (MIC). The MIC will be a regional transfer point for a series of ground access modes, including bus and rail transit systems, commuter, inter-city and high speed rail systems, and rental car facilities. The landside APM system, in conjunction with the MIG, is expected to relieve congestion on the terminal curbs and roadways at MIA.
   This paper will provide an overall review of the planned APM systems at MIA. In addition, unique design features relating to these APM systems and how they have been planned for integration into the overall airport redevelopment program will be discussed.
