AU  - Parker, TJ
AU  - Mizera, RF
ED  - Sproule, WJ
ED  - Neumann, ES
ED  - Lynch, SW
TI  - Personal Rapid Transit (PRT) - An intermodal connector
T2  - AUTOMATED PEOPLE MOVERS VI: CREATIVE ACCESS FOR MAJOR ACTIVITY CENTERS
LA  - English
CP  - 6th International Conference on Automated People Movers
AB  - Since late 1993, The Regional Transportation Authority and its consultant, Consoer Townsend Envirodyne Engineers, Inc. have been involved in a development program to produce the first-ever operational Personal Rapid Transit (PRT) System. As this development process has evolved, it has become increasingly evident that a marketable system will soon be available for deployment in many locales throughout the world.
   Although many of us have heard and read about PRT systems, no one has ever built one for revenue or non-revenue service. Consequently, a considerable amount of speculation exists as to the viability of such a system in todays transit world.
   PRT systems must have a distinct advantage over other forms of transportation in order to make it attractive and be able to be implemented in an environment which is primarily hostile to anything which violates the suburban landscape. In order to achieve these objectives, a PRT system must be flexible, fast, and most importantly, economical to operate. In addition, a PRT system must be able to achieve integration into a community in the least obtrusive manner possible and, at the same time, serve its ridership base conveniently.
   This abstract will look at one form of use for a PRT system. That use will be to serve as an intermodal link between one alternative form of transportation in the suburbs. This paper will address the following:
   Alignment
   Stations
   Maintenance Yard
   Ridership
   Fare Management
   The PRT system depicted is a fictional alignment which could be located in any number of suburban locales acid does not reflect any long range planning concept.
   Stations will also be discussed; as to how these stations will be handled to fit into the community yet situated to handle the anticipated ridership as well.
   The paper will address how the needs of the system are to be met and the facilities required to serve this system.
   Ultimately, the success of PRT will be judged by its ability to attract sustainable ridership as well as recover O&M expenditures through the farebox. To that end, this paper will examine ridership potential and fare management strategies afforded by this technology.
