TI  - Advanced transit and prosperity
T2  - AUTOMATED PEOPLE MOVERS VI: CREATIVE ACCESS FOR MAJOR ACTIVITY CENTERS
LA  - English
CP  - 6th International Conference on Automated People Movers
AB  - Transit advocates have long argued for improved transit services based on vital social needs. Despite the overwhelming amount of evidence that advocates have gathered to support the need for transit, transit's share of the transportation market continues to decline.
   While society needs mobility, and problems with current prevalent modes continue to plague society, the apparent need for more transit service has yet to result in more demand. The reason for this is that transit advocates and providers have too narrowly focused on only one part of a three-part demand cycle. While necessity is acclaimed to be the mother of invention, demand for that invention only begins when it begins to provide a valued service. Service is the second part of the demand cycle, and a small amount of transit discussion addresses how to provide comparable Service to existing transport modes. Yet providing a valued service will not generate strong demand for a product. That valued service must lead to greater prosperity if demand is to grow significantly.
   This paper addresses the three-part demand cycle, and challenges transit advocates to focus on increasing prosperity to accomplish their objective of broadening transit service. The paper also addresses the need for applying advanced transit technologies and development approaches if transit service is to become a significant part of the transportation industry.
